Harvard students take a course on rest habits
This year, a new course at Harvard University has allowed its students to sleep longer, in an attempt to combat the increasingly widespread culture of studying all night long, stimulated by caffeine.
One academic noted that students at the world’s number one university are often misguided by what goes into the basics of how to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, designed the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to create the course after giving a talk about the impact sleep deprivation had on learning.
“At the end of the talk, a girl came up to me and said, ‘Why are you telling me all this now, in my final year?’
He said no one had ever told him about the importance of sleep, which surprised me,” she told The Telegraph.
The course, first implemented this year, explains to students the basic concepts of how good sleep habits improve academic and sports performance, in addition to general well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the University’s health services, said the university decided to introduce the course after learning that some students suffered from severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The course, which lasts one hour, includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one section there is an image of a bedroom, where students have to click on coffee cups, curtains, bamboos and books to receive information about the effects of caffeine and light, about how sports performance affects lack of sleep, and about the importance of maintaining a bedtime routine.
In another section, participants are informed about how long-term sleep deprivation can increase their risk of heart attacks, strokes, depression, and cancer.
Below, a campus map with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily route.
“We know that students’ behavior will not change immediately.
But we believe they have the right to know, as one has the right to know the health effects of smoking cigarettes,” Professor Czeisler said.
The culture of pride in staying up all night still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and the growing pressure on students make sleep deprivation an ever-growing problem.
Making sure you enjoy good quality sleep for long enough should be a student’s “secret weapon” to combat stress, fatigue and anxiety, he added, even to avoid gaining weight, since sleep deprivation puts the brain into starvation mode and makes students always hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian who studied Chemistry and Physical Biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course, having attended one of his classes the last year during his first year at Harvard.
Raymond commented that the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to promote the course across campus.
The next step, he hopes, is to ask postgraduate students to undertake a similar study program before joining the competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students consider setting an alarm when they go to sleep and when they wake up, and be aware of the harmful effects of the “blue light” emitted by electronic displays and LED lights, which can alter circadian rhythm harmony and cause sleep problems.
