Lieutenant Colonel and Reverend Bernard Vann won the award on 29 September 1918 for the attack on Bellenglise and Lehaucourt.
However, he was shot by a sniper four days later and never knew he had won the most important British military honor.
His two grandsons unearthed a memorial tombstone at a Saturday parade in Rushden, Northamptonshire.
One of his grandchildren, Michael Vann, said it was "magnificently symbolic" that the tombstone was presented exactly 100 years after his grandfather's award-winning feat.
According to The London Gazette, on September 29, 1918, Lieutenant Colonel Vann led his battalion through the Saint-Quentin Canal "through a very thick fog and under the intense fire of guns and machine guns".
He later ran towards the line of fire and, with "maximum courage", advanced the line before throwing himself over a cannon with one hand and stunned three members of the detachment.
The lieutenant colonel was shot down by a German sniper on 4 October 1918, just one month before the war ended.
Michael Vann (72) said that his grandfather's actions were a feat he could never match, which produces a sense of humility.
He and his brother, Dr. James Vann, also left a wreath after the parade, led by the Brentwood Imperial Youth Band.
Michael Vann said he felt very honored to be part of the show and added that the courage of a true hero is demonstrated by the support he will receive from many people.
