Germany's New Warship Delayed Again
The new frigate of the German Navy should have been completed in 2014 to replace the old warships of the Cold War era, but will not do so at least until next year due to faulty systems and an increase in cost, according to local media.
The completion of the "Rheinland-Pfalz", the main ship of the new Baden-Württemberg-class frigates, has been postponed until the first half of 2019, according to the newspaper Die Zeit, citing a military spokesman.
The ship should have joined the Navy in 2014, but post-construction problems have marked the deadlines for this ambitious project.
The four Baden-Württemberg-class ships commissioned by the Navy in 2007 will replace the old Bremen-class frigates.
It is believed to include a powerful cannon, a set of anti-aircraft and anti-ship missiles, as well as stealth technology such as reduced radar, infrared and acoustic signatures.
Other outstanding features include longer periods between maintenance: it should be possible to use the new frigates for up to two years without passing through national ports.
However, these continued delays imply that the avant-garde ships, which were expected to project Germany as a powerful force abroad, will already be obsolete by the time they go into operation, according to Die Zeit.
The unfortunate frigate F125 made news last year, when the German Navy rejected the ship and returned it to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
It was the first time the Navy had returned a ship to the builder once delivered.
Few details are known of the reasons for the return, but German media have cited several "material and technical defects" of the ship that made it unusable if used in combat missions.
The technical problems are significant, as approximately 120 sailors, half the crew needed for the old Bremen-class frigates, operate on Baden-Württemberg-class ships.
In addition, it has also been known that the weight of the ship is excessive, which reduces its performance and limits the Navy's ability to add future improvements.
The 7,000-ton "Rheinland-Pfalz" is believed to weigh twice as much as similar-class ships used by the Germans during World War II.
Aside from defective materials, the cost of the project, which includes crew training, also begins to pose a problem.
It is believed to have reached an astonishing 3.1 billion euros ($3.6 billion) from an initial budget of 2.2 billion euros.
The problems of the new frigates have become a matter of particular importance, given recent warnings that Germany’s maritime military power is being weakened.
This year, Hans-Peter Bartels, head of the defence committee of the German Parliament, acknowledged that the Navy "is running out of ships that can be used".
The official said the situation had worsened over time because the old ships were no longer used, but no new ones were provided as spares.
He regretted that none of the frigates of the Baden-Württemberg class could join the Navy.
The National Foundation spies on the secret life of bats
A new research carried out on a farm in the Scottish Highlands aims to discover how bats use the landscape to feed themselves.
The findings are expected to provide new data on the behavior of these unique flying mammals and help with future conservation activities.
The study of the scientists of the National Foundation of Scotland will follow soprano and common bats, in addition to northern and water bats in the Inverewe Botanical Garden, located in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed at key locations of the property to track the activities of bats during the season.
UK National Health Service volunteers and staff will also conduct mobile surveys with portable detectors.
The sound analysis of the recordings by experts will determine the sound frequency of the bats and what each species does.
With this information, a report and habitat map will be created to create a detailed landscape-scale picture of your behavior.
Rob Dewar, a natural conservation advisor at the National Foundation of Scotland, hopes the results will show which areas of the habitat are most important to bats and how each species uses them.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as creating meadows, and how to improve forest maintenance for bats and other associated species.
The population of bats in Scotland and the rest of the United Kingdom has declined considerably in the last century.
The construction and restoration of buildings threaten bats, as they affect nests and can cause habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lighting also pose a risk, as do paperflies and chemical treatments used in building materials, as well as attacks by domestic cats.
In fact, bats are not blind.
However, due to their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when they have to catch a prey.
They use a sophisticated echo locating technique to locate insects and obstacles that get in the way of their flight.
The National Foundation of Scotland, responsible for taking care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land throughout the country, takes bats very seriously.
It has ten experts with the appropriate training, who carry out surveys, inspections of nests and, sometimes, rescues on a regular basis.
The organization has even created Scotland's first and only bat reserve at the Threat Estate, located in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
The estate's administrator, David Thompson, claims that it is the ideal territory for the species.
“Here at Threate, we have a large area for bats,” he says.
"We have old buildings, many old trees and a good habitat.
But we still don’t know many aspects of bats, so the work we do here and on other properties will help us better understand what they need to grow.”
It emphasizes the importance of checking for bats before doing maintenance tasks on properties, as it may be that the possible involuntary destruction of a single maternity nest kills more than 400 females and young, which could lead to the disappearance of an entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill, attack, annoy and destroy their nests.
Elisabeth Ferrell, an official with the Scottish Bat Conservation Foundation, has encouraged people to take a step forward to help.
“We still have a lot to learn from bats, and in the case of some of our species, we don’t have enough data on their population.”
