Below are some important facts about Palu and Donggala, on the island of Celebes:
Palu is the capital of the province of Central Celebes, located at the end of a narrow bay on the west coast of the island Celebes, with an estimated population of 379,800 people in 2017.
The city was celebrating its 40th anniversary when the earthquake and tsunami occurred.
Donggala is a regency that extends along more than 300 km of coastline to the northwest of Celebes Island.
The regency, an administrative region lower than a province, had a population of approximately 299,200 people in 2017.
Fisheries and agriculture are the pillars of the economy of Central Celebes province, especially in the coastal region of Donggala.
Nickel mining is also important in the province, but is mainly concentrated in Morowali, on the coast of the other extreme of Celebes.
Palu and Donggala have suffered several tsunamis in the past 100 years, according to Indonesia’s disaster mitigation agency.
In 1938, a tsunami killed more than 200 people and destroyed hundreds of houses in Donggala.
In 1996, a tsunami in western Donggala killed nine people.
Indonesia is located in the Pacific Fire Belt and earthquakes occur there with some frequency.
Below are the main earthquakes and tsunamis of recent years:
2004: On 26 December, a large earthquake on the west coast of the Indonesian province of Ace, north of Sumatra, caused a tsunami that affected 14 countries and killed 226,000 people on the coast of the Indian Ocean, more than half of those in Aceh.
2005: A series of strong earthquakes hit the west coast of Sumatra in late March and early April.
Thousands of people died on the island of Nias, off the coast of Sumatra.
2006: A magnitude 6.8 earthquake struck southern Java, Indonesia's most populous island, and caused a tsunami that shattered the southern coast and killed nearly 700 people.
2009: An earthquake with a magnitude of 7.6 rocked a populous area of the city of Padang, the capital of West Sumatra province.
More than 1,100 people died.
2010: An earthquake with a magnitude of 7.5 shook one of the islands of Mentawai, off the coast of Sumatra, and caused a tsunami of up to 10 meters that destroyed dozens of villages and killed about 300 people.
2016: A mild earthquake affected Pidie Jaya’s regency in Aceh and caused destruction and panic, as the population recalled the devastation of the deadly 2004 earthquake and tsunami.
This time, no tsunami occurred, but more than 100 people died from the buildings that fell.
2018: A series of large earthquakes occurred on the tourist island of Lombok in Indonesia that killed more than 500 people, mostly in the north of the island.
The earthquake destroyed thousands of buildings and left thousands of tourists trapped temporarily.
